</node>
<node id="United States">
  <data key="d0">United States</data>
  <data key="d1">country</data>
  <data key="d2">The United States is a global power with a multifaceted and often contradictory role in international relations. It has pursued secret diplomatic talks with Cuba, proposing to lift the long-standing trade embargo and provide Starlink access, while simultaneously demanding the release of political prisoners and compensation for U.S.-owned assets seized after the Cuban Revolution. Despite maintaining an energy blockade on the island, it has authorized a Russian oil tanker to deliver fuel to Cuba, effectively circumventing its own restrictions. Cuban President Miguel Díaz-Canel has signaled openness to negotiations, suggesting a potential shift in bilateral relations.

In its geopolitical posture, the United States is portrayed by Russian ideologue Alexander Dugin as a foreign power seeking to undermine sovereign states resisting integration into a unified Eurasian union. European officials have questioned its reliability as a NATO ally, particularly regarding commitments to European defense against Russian aggression, though Lithuanian leaders advocate for stronger U.S.-European unity. Political opposition to U.S. influence has emerged in Europe, notably from Patriots for Europe, which resisted proposed U.S.-EU free trade agreements in October 2025.

The United States has cultivated close ties with Hungary under Prime Minister Viktor Orbán, marked by direct political backing from U.S. officials. Vice President J.D. Vance visited Hungary five days before its election to bolster Orbán’s campaign and confer political legitimacy, with additional visits planned. Secretary of State Marco Rubio also engaged in diplomatic outreach. U.S. envoy Jey D. Vens was dispatched to oppose EU interference and affirm Hungary’s sovereignty. Orbán claims the United States will participate in a proposed peace summit with Russia in Budapest and has asserted that U.S. sanctions on Russian oil are being lifted. Cooperation extends to infrastructure, including the Adriatic Pipeline, which Hungarian officials regard as a strategic outcome.

The United States is also associated with Donald Trump, whose administration is credited with deepening U.S.-Hungary cooperation and unlocking economic potential for Hungary. Republican politicians remain active within the U.S. political system, and transnational linkages have been established, including contacts between U.S. Republicans and Germany’s AfD party through Marcus Frontmeyer. The United States is further identified as the primary origin and hub of the “white jihad” phenomenon among neo-Nazis, whose ideologies have spread into Europe.

In a separate context, the United States is cited as engaging in a senseless war against Iran alongside Israel, an action said to exacerbate Europe’s energy crisis. It is also described as a former collaborator with the European Union and the former British Empire, now governed by figures perceived as marginalizing EU integration. In a hypothetical conflict scenario, the United States is depicted as capable of disabling Russian communication infrastructure, including Starlink and Windows systems. One conflicting source claims the United States is not mentioned in a given text, likely reflecting an error or omission. Overall, the United States functions simultaneously as a diplomatic interlocutor, a perceived destabilizing force, a technological actor, and a polarizing symbol in global politics.&lt;SEP&gt;United States is the country where CPAC is based and whose political figures, including Donald Trump, actively supported Viktor Orbán.&lt;SEP&gt;United States is a country mentioned as a destination for billions of forints transferred by oligarchs linked to Orbán.&lt;SEP&gt;United States, through its Defense Intelligence Agency, corroborates information regarding North Korea’s military shipments to Russia.&lt;SEP&gt;United States is the country operating the B-1B Lancer bombers that conducted strikes against Iran. relation United States B-1B Lancer operation,command,control United States operates the B-1B Lancer bombers that launched strikes against Iran from the United Kingdom.&lt;SEP&gt;United States is a country involved in security relations with the United Kingdom, seeking to use British military bases and engaging in diplomatic tensions with the UK government over Iran policy.</data>
