<node id="Russia">
  <data key="d0">Russia</data>
  <data key="d1">country</data>
  <data key="d2">Russia is a country led by Vladimir Putin, engaged in an ongoing war of aggression against Ukraine, which it invaded in 2022 and continues to justify under the framework of its “special military operation” (SVO). Russia seeks to occupy historical Ukrainian territories, including Sumy and Kharkiv, and is perceived by many European nations—particularly Germany, Lithuania, and Poland—as a direct threat to NATO’s eastern flank. It is actively preparing for potential conflict with NATO by 2030, with plans involving hybrid warfare tactics such as drone warfare, migrant pressure via Belarus, propaganda targeting Russian-speaking populations in the Baltics, and limited conventional invasions, including scenarios to seize Narva or sever the Suwałki Corridor. Russia has also threatened limited nuclear use to deter NATO intervention.

Russia’s military relies on commercial satellite systems like Starlink for command and control, despite longstanding communication failures evident in prior conflicts in Chechnya and Georgia. Its armed forces have gained extensive combat experience in Ukraine and operate modified Tu-214R aircraft for signals intelligence. The Russian military has received substantial support from North Korea, including approximately 14,000 troops deployed since 2024, over 8–11 million rounds of ammunition, and advanced weaponry, in exchange for Russian military technology valued between $7.67 billion and $14.4 billion. North Korean soldiers operate under Russian command, conducting artillery strikes from Russian territory and participating in demining and infrastructure restoration efforts near the Ukrainian border.

Russia’s energy sector remains central to its geopolitical strategy. It supplies 90% of Hungary’s oil and 95% of its natural gas, and is constructing Hungary’s new atomic power station. Discounted crude oil exports to Hungary enable inflated retail prices and substantial profits for Hungarian state-owned energy firms, while the Druzhba pipeline—damaged by Russian airstrikes on January 27, 2024, at the Brody Pumping Station—has disrupted oil transit to Ukraine. Russia’s energy exports have bolstered its state budget amid global price increases, even as it faces the 20th package of EU sanctions, opposed by Slovakia due to the pipeline’s strategic importance.

Russia is accused of extensive information warfare, electoral interference, and hybrid operations across Europe, particularly in Hungary and Moldova. Russian intelligence agencies, including the GRU and SVR RF, are alleged to have infiltrated Hungarian institutions, disseminated disinformation via RT Balkan and Magyar Nemzet, and orchestrated “honey trap” operations to compromise officials. Russian operatives are linked to efforts to influence Hungary’s parliamentary elections, including by portraying the opposition as Western puppets and promoting narratives that align with Kremlin rhetoric. Viktor Orbán’s government has been described as subordinating Hungary’s national interests to Russia’s, with direct diplomatic contact between Russian Foreign Minister Lavrov and Hungarian officials, and reports of cash and valuables being transported between the two nations. A 12-point bilateral agreement has deepened cooperation in energy, education, sports, and nuclear fuel, including Russian teacher recruitment for Russian language programs and joint exchange initiatives.

Russia is also associated with transnational criminal networks, including ties to Russian mobster Semen Mogilevich and money laundering through Donald Trump’s real estate ventures. It maintains a strategic alliance with Iran and is suspected of receiving pharmaceuticals from North Korea. Russian state media and propaganda, often echoed by Hungarian political figures, portray Russia as a bulwark against Western hegemony, while Hungarian nationalist rallies have included chants demanding Russians “go home,” highlighting domestic tensions. Despite claims by some that Russia has not attacked EU member states, its actions—including pipeline sabotage, cyberattacks, and support for separatist movements in Estonia’s Ida-Viru County—are widely interpreted as acts of aggression under international law. European officials, including Lithuanian authorities, view Russia’s actions as rooted in deep-seated imperial ideology, extending beyond the current regime. While some, like Robert Fico and Viktor Orbán, argue for negotiations and claim Russia will not be weakened by the war, the broader international consensus holds that any lasting peace in Europe requires Ukraine’s consent and Russia’s withdrawal from occupied territories.&lt;SEP&gt;Russia is a country that is described as having influenced North Korea to become a production base, contributing to improved conditions there.</data>
