</node>
<node id="Slovakia">
  <data key="d0">Slovakia</data>
  <data key="d1">country</data>
  <data key="d2">Slovakia is a European Union member state and a neighboring country to Ukraine, with its border near Uzhhorod—a region historically linked to Ukrainian and Russian criminal networks following the Soviet collapse. Led by Prime Minister Robert Fico, Slovakia has developed a complex political and geopolitical profile marked by domestic turbulence and alignment with Hungary under Viktor Orbán. Fico’s government has coordinated with Hungary to obstruct EU sanctions against Russia, including efforts to remove Russian individuals from sanctions lists, delay the 18th sanctions package, and secure exemptions for Russian oil and gas imports. Slovakia opposes the 20th EU sanctions package, citing its reliance on the Druzhba pipeline for oil transit, and disputes claims that a Russian strike on January 27 damaged the pipeline, instead advocating for a fact-finding mission in Ukraine.

Domestically, Slovakia has experienced political instability, including a parliamentary vote of no confidence and electoral law reforms aimed at consolidating power ahead of potential elections in 2026 or 2027. An investigation has been launched by the General Prosecutor’s Office against Fico over allegations of treason related to electricity supplies to Ukraine. Far-right parties in Slovakia, aligned with the broader European far-right movement, have expressed pro-Russian sympathies and criticized Donald Trump’s foreign policy. Reports indicate Kremlin and Hungarian interference in Slovak elections, particularly targeting the SMER party and the creation of the Hlas party to sway electoral outcomes. Hungary has also allegedly orchestrated migrant flows into Slovakia to influence its parliamentary elections.

Slovakia has contributed militarily to Ukraine’s defense by transferring 13 MiG-29 fighter jets in 2023 and has ordered 14 F-16 Block 70/72 aircraft to modernize its air force, relying in the interim on air defense support from Hungary, Poland, and the Czech Republic. It has ceased diesel exports to Ukraine, mirroring Hungary’s decision, though it remains eligible for petroleum supplies from Croatia. Slovakia receives natural gas via the Adriatic Pipeline (JANAF) without complications, and has sought airspace transit permissions from neighboring nations to facilitate Fico’s diplomatic travel to Moscow.

Bratislava, Slovakia’s capital, alongside Budapest, has been identified as a hub for leaked information on EU sanctions negotiations, with recorded conversations confirming coordination with Moscow. Slovak officials, including those connected to the Dubai-based Russian oil trader 2Rivers, have collaborated with Russian intermediaries such as Siyarto—who reported to Russian Deputy Energy Minister Sorokin—to lobby against sanctions and discredit EU leadership, including EU High Representative Josep Borrell. Additionally, Slovakia is the country where Рогоч received a life sentence for his role in manufacturing and detonating a bomb.&lt;SEP&gt;Slovakia is a European country led by Robert Fico, experiencing political, budgetary, and economic instability. It is under pressure from Moscow-Belarus actions and faces internal dissent over pro-Russian policies, including protests with slogans like "Ruszkik haza!"&lt;SEP&gt;Slovakia is a country that supports Ukraine's accession to the European Union and is led by Prime Minister Robert Fico, who engaged in diplomatic talks with Zelensky.&lt;SEP&gt;Slovakia is the country led by Robert Fico, whose government supported Ukraine's accession to the European Union and maintained diplomatic ties with Russia. relation Robert Fico Slovakia leadership, political representation Robert Fico is the Prime Minister of Slovakia and represents its foreign policy stance, including support for Ukraine’s EU membership and engagement with Russia.</data>
