<node id="Hungary">
  <data key="d0">Hungary</data>
  <data key="d1">country</data>
  <data key="d2">Hungary is a European Union and NATO member state in Central Europe, governed since 2010 by Prime Minister Viktor Orbán and his Fidesz party, which has systematically consolidated power through electoral manipulation, media control, and erosion of democratic institutions. Orbán’s government promotes an illiberal, nationalist agenda centered on defending Hungarian sovereignty against perceived external interference from the European Union and NATO, while cultivating close ties with Russia. Hungary has repeatedly blocked or delayed EU sanctions against Russia, advocated for the lifting of energy sanctions, and demanded the restoration of oil transit via the Druzhba pipeline, citing energy security and economic stability as justifications. The country sources approximately 90% of its oil and 95% of its gas from Russia, with profits from discounted Russian energy funneled into political foundations linked to Orbán.

Hungary’s foreign policy, under Minister of Foreign Affairs Péter Szijjártó, has been accused of acting as a conduit for Russian influence within the EU, including transmitting confidential information to Russian officials, lobbying for the removal of Russian individuals from sanctions lists, and coordinating with Slovakia to dilute EU sanctions. Hungary has refused to support EU joint statements on Venezuela, opposed the use of frozen Russian assets for Ukrainian reparations, and denied Ukraine’s claim that it defends Europe. The government has also ceased diesel exports to Ukraine, detained Ukrainian cash-in-transit officers near Budapest, deported Ukrainian citizens, and allegedly denied medical care to a detained Ukrainian with disabilities. Ukraine and international observers have accused Hungary of conducting espionage in Zakarpattia, facilitating illicit financial flows from Russia, and deploying disinformation campaigns using AI-generated content, deepfakes, and state media to foster hostility toward Ukraine and justify Orbán’s policies.

Domestically, Hungary has faced mass protests against Orbán’s pro-Moscow alignment, particularly around the anniversary of the 1848 revolution, while pro-Orbán rallies have been supported by state resources and nationalist rhetoric. The 2026 parliamentary elections are anticipated to be highly contested, with the Tisza party emerging as a major challenger to Fidesz. Allegations of electoral fraud—including vote buying, coercion, gerrymandering, and state media dominance—have been documented, alongside claims of Russian interference aimed at securing Orbán’s victory. Opposition figures such as Péter Márki-Zay and Péter Magyar have accused Orbán’s government of treason, corruption, and allowing Russian intelligence to interfere in elections. Magyar, who is set to become prime minister following a political shift, has called for investigations into oligarchs linked to Orbán and urged law enforcement agencies to prosecute those who have harmed the Hungarian people.

Hungary’s sovereignty and political future are central themes in Orbán’s narrative, which frames EU pressure as an existential threat. The country has had approximately €18 billion in EU funds frozen due to non-compliance with anti-corruption reforms and alignment with Russian interests. Despite Orbán’s rhetoric, public opinion consistently supports EU and NATO membership. Hungary has also been implicated in transnational criminal activity, including smuggling, tax evasion, and organized crime networks operating in Budapest during the 1990s. The government has offered assistance to Iran following the 2024 pager attack and served as a transit route for Robert Fico’s trip to Moscow. Under Orbán’s leadership, Hungary has adopted a 12-point agreement with Russia to deepen economic, energy, and cultural ties, and has been commended by Vladimir Putin and Donald Trump for its anti-immigration stance and resistance to EU norms. However, recent developments suggest a potential political transition, with Tisza’s electoral gains and growing public dissent signaling a possible shift away from Russia-aligned policies.&lt;SEP&gt;Hungary is a country led by Orbán, engaged in a complex conflict with Ukraine and characterized by policies associated with "Orbanism."</data>
