<node id="Orbán">
  <data key="d0">Orbán</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Orbán is the Prime Minister of Hungary and the long-standing leader of the Fidesz party, having held power for 16 years and overseeing extensive electoral reforms, media consolidation, and the erosion of democratic institutions. He is widely described as the de facto ruler of Hungary, maintaining control through patronage systems, voter coercion, altered electoral boundaries, and state-aligned media, with approximately 80% of the country’s news outlets now under government influence. Orbán campaigns relentlessly on nationalist and anti-EU narratives, prominently using Ukraine as a central theme to justify domestic economic grievances, block EU financial aid and sanctions targeting Russia, and rally support ahead of elections. He has repeatedly opposed the European Union’s proposal to use frozen Russian assets for reparations to Ukraine, labeling it a “new level of escalation,” and has actively blocked €90 billion in allocated aid. Orbán has also halted diesel fuel shipments to Ukraine, accused Ukraine of refusing to repair the Druzhba pipeline, and conditioned the resumption of Ukrainian transit shipments on the pipeline’s activation.

Orbán maintains close, publicly acknowledged ties with Russian President Vladimir Putin, with whom he has engaged in diplomatic correspondence, phone calls, and summit proposals. In these interactions, Orbán has described Putin as not an aggressor, criticized the West for provoking the war through NATO expansion, and metaphorically positioned himself as “Putin’s mouse” aiding a “lion,” a remark he later characterized as normal and non-compromising. Russia, in turn, has signaled strong opposition to any EU use of frozen assets, viewing it as a threat to its sovereignty and economic interests. Orbán’s regime is accused of collaborating with Russian intelligence services, benefiting from cheap Russian oil, and being the target of Russian disinformation campaigns that portray him as Hungary’s sole defender against Western interference. His political movement is associated with separatist agitation in Transcarpathia, anti-Ukrainian propaganda, and the use of Kremlin-linked “spoiler technology” to destabilize opposition efforts.

Orbán’s leadership has been marked by resistance to anti-corruption reforms, allegations of money laundering by Fidesz-linked oligarchs, and systematic vote-buying in impoverished regions. He has faced domestic protests, including rallies where demonstrators chanted “Dictator” and “Russians home,” and was booed at a campaign event in Dęır, which he blamed on pro-Ukrainian sentiment. Despite declining poll numbers and allegations of a Russian-backed sabotage plot targeting him, Orbán continues to frame his rule as essential to keeping Hungary out of war, invoking the slogan “For a Sovereign Hungary.” He has also leveraged Donald Trump’s image to legitimize his political stance. Although he recently acknowledged electoral defeat and stepped down as prime minister, his influence persists, and his regime’s institutional legacy remains deeply entrenched. Orbán’s political identity is defined by a fusion of authoritarian governance, anti-Western rhetoric, pro-Russian alignment, and the instrumentalization of Ukraine’s conflict to consolidate domestic power.&lt;SEP&gt;Orbán is a political figure who transitioned from a young activist opposing communism with support from George Soros to an autocratic leader, engaging in conflict with the West, implementing controversial laws, and opposing George Soros.</data>
