<node id="Fidesz">
  <data key="d0">Fidesz</data>
  <data key="d1">organization</data>
  <data key="d2">Fidesz is the Hungarian political party led by Viktor Orbán that has been in power for 16 years and continues to dominate the country’s political landscape. It has consolidated authority through systematic control of state institutions, including the executive, judicial, prosecutorial, central bank, and intelligence agencies, while also dominating approximately 90% of Hungary’s media landscape—encompassing all television channels and nearly all FM radio stations—and controlling the majority of advertising space. The party has repeatedly manipulated electoral boundaries since 2012 to entrench its dominance, most recently redrawing district lines ahead of the 2026 parliamentary elections and implementing a mixed-member proportional voting system that disproportionately favors the winning party through a compensation mechanism. Critics and protesters have labeled it “Dirty Fidesz,” citing widespread allegations of authoritarian practices, including large-scale voter bribery, electoral manipulation, and the use of blackmail during campaigns, which have reportedly produced implausibly high vote shares—ranging from 80% to 100%—in certain constituencies. Fidesz has also been implicated in disseminating AI-generated disinformation, including deepfake videos featuring opposition figures and fabricated content, such as a false video of a girl awaiting her father killed in Ukraine. The party has engaged in controversial legislative actions, such as introducing a bill to temporarily confiscate funds from Ukraine’s Oshchadbank. Despite its entrenched position, Fidesz is currently experiencing declining popularity, trailing behind the Tisza coalition in opinion polls, prompting internal panic and reportedly intensified support from Russian intelligence. Fidesz positions itself as a “party of peace” under Orbán’s leadership, framing the opposition as a “party of war,” while maintaining close ties to Moscow and attracting international right-wing conservative support. Its rule is further characterized by the enrichment of its inner circle and the subordination of democratic norms to partisan interests.&lt;SEP&gt;Fidesz is the ruling political party in Hungary, implicitly referenced as the source of disinformation campaigns and political accusations against the opposition, described by Peter Magyar as using “typical Fidesz panic and lies.”&lt;SEP&gt;Fidesz is the political party led by Orbán, which experienced a sharp decline in polling before the Hungarian elections and lost power due to leaked communications with Russia.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-aeeb3e654a660cb7b38dfc9d61222bc9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e84aa583f7aa058a2cdc38864b8c765a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bae0e37e11b33519772a72128c43c6ee&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2886b7cb500c955cf1d8671ed22bd946&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c99964a997545fd96cbae2fac33e426b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-583ccb318ed3bd5eb71b569940315d4f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-26fcbf6510a404d136a66a46e0584357&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-81536517f133c3a5924be660cac3eb05&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a3aab01d8a12e8135d55b3153fc006d0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8fa6adba441e776b293e92361b9880d1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-49d9496e943d94ccc071cf105396b990&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-95251bcfc4d08a0a36c341b9a9e2da54&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2369463d8ede9e477cfaf832815ef3c5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b6bcd039eb9ab628a1ffb566a855dd2b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-867b81690ecba5bc75830acd44c39131&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3e4bedfc173098465d955c0364c5de9b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a810084503e65cb067ff1fc3c7a05189</data>
