<node id="Tisza">
  <data key="d0">Tisza</data>
  <data key="d1">organization</data>
  <data key="d2">Tisza is a Hungarian opposition political party led by Péter Márki-Zay, positioned as the primary challenger to Fidesz in the country’s parliamentary elections. It has emerged as the leading force in most independent opinion polls, currently polling at 49%, and is widely regarded as the main democratic alternative to Viktor Orbán’s 16-year dominance. Tisza is supported by a coalition of opposition parties that have withdrawn from direct competition to consolidate votes against Fidesz, and it competes specifically for national party list votes under Hungary’s mixed electoral system. The party has gained significant electoral momentum amid widespread public discontent over economic hardship and corruption scandals under Orbán’s rule. Tisza is portrayed as a catalyst for democratic renewal, with its potential victory framed as essential to restoring Hungary’s alignment with European Union values and ending Orbán’s authoritarian governance. The European Union and advocacy groups such as EU Made Simple have implicitly or explicitly endorsed Tisza’s candidacy as the only viable path to democratic reform. Russian intelligence operatives have targeted Tisza with disinformation campaigns, attempting to label it a “party of war” aligned with Ukraine and fabricating criminal allegations against its members, including Maria Gurozo and Ervin Nadem, using AI-generated videos. Tisza has also held public rallies in Budapest, including one featuring Joltt Hegedus, and its rise has been linked to leaked conversations involving Orbán and Russian officials. Despite some descriptions referring to Tisza as a “coalition,” the consistent identification of Péter Márki-Zay as its leader and the unified electoral strategy indicate that Tisza functions primarily as a unified political party, not a loose alliance. No credible evidence suggests the existence of a separate entity named Tisza; all references converge on this single, cohesive opposition movement.&lt;SEP&gt;Tisza is a political party in Hungary whose IT specialists were targeted for recruitment by Hungarian special services.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-ad59dda33fb37c7a475f7200ea184cf8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-aeeb3e654a660cb7b38dfc9d61222bc9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2886b7cb500c955cf1d8671ed22bd946&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-443c22f60ed93ec379e718efa356a140&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-00452022e84a0076582b1330b967245d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-583ccb318ed3bd5eb71b569940315d4f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-325a7fb30b39d268db124a71f1e8acc7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a3aab01d8a12e8135d55b3153fc006d0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2369463d8ede9e477cfaf832815ef3c5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b6bcd039eb9ab628a1ffb566a855dd2b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1561937403235278917e112e7843f5b0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a810084503e65cb067ff1fc3c7a05189&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-63ebd542c6a2099ce773883107cf0bc9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e1c1527de328b9a19ce7197568a1196b</data>
