<node id="Druzhba">
  <data key="d0">Druzhba</data>
  <data key="d1">location</data>
  <data key="d2">Druzhba is a major oil pipeline system that transports Russian oil to Hungary and Slovakia at discounted rates, enabling Hungarian energy company MOL (MO) to supply fuel at lower prices than alternative sources. The pipeline has become a focal point of geopolitical tension, particularly following a Russian airstrike on the Brody pumping station in Ukraine on January 27, which damaged its Ukrainian section and disrupted transit. Ukraine initially blocked operations on its territory, prompting Hungary to seize Ukrainian funds and threaten further actions until the pipeline was reopened. Hungarian Prime Minister Viktor Orbán made the restoration of Druzhba’s transit a precondition for approving further financial credit to Ukraine, using the pipeline as a tool of political leverage. The damage caused by the Russian strike has been acknowledged as a deliberate act of infrastructure targeting, and repair efforts are now scheduled to proceed with funding and technical support from the European Union. Druzhba’s operational status is thus not only an energy infrastructure issue but also a critical element in the broader political and economic dynamics between Russia, Ukraine, Hungary, and the EU.&lt;SEP&gt;Druzhba is an oil pipeline that Slovakia and Hungary are seeking to restore, and whose operation has been disrupted by Ukrainian actions.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-01a82c39b89d6badd9ffe2e8f2cc363a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-870499425ae897e4d4a7fe9c0c2b515c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-141360bcc1e8268affe7476ca1b210ea&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-59d39825ceed8bfe99406c6b226d590f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-febe32c9e0da364a16a64ecb34a3ae7b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-21313de66f58c55ed37fed59c551bfe8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0b9d4541f93fbe1abbecc6f52128db7e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fc1feb8e698e39594612de628b9b30f8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-204b60f8b5f56bb209e8ca6cc9af48f9</data>
