<node id="North Korea">
  <data key="d0">North Korea</data>
  <data key="d1">country</data>
  <data key="d2">North Korea, officially known as the Democratic People’s Republic of Korea, is a country led by Supreme Leader Kim Jong Un, who exercises complete authority over its military, government, and foreign operations. North Korea has actively supported Russia’s invasion of Ukraine, publicly pledging assistance to Moscow and deploying substantial military forces to the conflict zone. According to multiple reports, approximately 10,000 to 14,000 North Korean soldiers were sent to Russia in 2024, with nearly half estimated to have been killed in action. These troops have participated in a range of combat and support roles, including artillery strikes, drone reconnaissance, demining operations in the Kursk Oblast, construction work, and frontline combat. Reports indicate that some soldiers were ordered to commit suicide to avoid capture, often using grenades when wounded.

North Korea has also supplied Russia with vast quantities of military equipment, including over 33,000 containers of arms—among them more than 15 million 152-mm artillery shells, 220 artillery pieces, 170-mm self-propelled howitzers, and 240-mm multiple rocket launchers—in exchange for advanced Russian military technologies. The country’s military involvement extends beyond direct combat: it has trained units with battlefield experience in Ukraine and is expected to integrate newly acquired warfare methods upon their return. In recognition of its fallen soldiers, North Korea has established a memorial complex in the Kursk Oblast, erected monuments and museums inspected by Kim Jong Un, and directed officials to maintain the graves of the deceased. A concert and a parade in Pyongyang, featuring the Russian flag, were held to honor these troops, underscoring the state’s official commemoration of their sacrifice.

Additionally, North Korea has mobilized its youth for potential military involvement in the conflict and continues to expand its defense industrial capacity, with missile production overseen by Kim Ju Ae and, controversially, reports suggest that Kim Jong Un’s 13-year-old daughter now heads the nation’s nuclear forces. The regime’s actions—including border provocations, aggressive rhetoric, and military cooperation with Russia—reflect a deliberate strategy of escalation and alignment with Moscow, despite international condemnation of its role in what is widely regarded as an illegal war.&lt;SEP&gt;North Korea is a country where the regime remains stable, K-Pop has no direct origin, and resort areas were created for specific purposes, as discussed in the context of the video.</data>
