<edge source="Russia" target="Ukraine">
  <data key="d8">21.0</data>
  <data key="d9">The (Russia, Ukraine) relation is defined by an ongoing war initiated by Russia through a full-scale military invasion, which is widely characterized under international law as an act of aggression and imperialist warfare. Russia’s stated objective, framed as a “Special Military Operation” (SVO), involves the occupation and control of Ukrainian regions including Sumy, Kharkiv, Donbas, and Kherson, with the strategic aim of establishing a security buffer zone across Ukraine. Ukraine is in a state of active, existential conflict with Russia, a condition that has become the central axis of European security policy and global geopolitical alignment. Ukraine’s resistance has exposed critical vulnerabilities in Russia’s military infrastructure, including the destruction of radar and air defense systems by Ukrainian drones, often enabled by NATO signals intelligence. Russia is also suspected of conducting intelligence operations to monitor and disrupt Western arms shipments to Ukraine, reflecting its broader goal of weakening European and transatlantic support for Ukraine’s defense.

Russia has employed information warfare tactics, including the creation of fake news websites by the Social Design Agency, to spread disinformation aimed at undermining Ukraine’s credibility and international standing. Russia’s strategic intent includes reducing Western military and political backing for Ukraine, a goal that has influenced diplomatic dynamics across Europe. Hungarian Prime Minister Viktor Orbán has argued that Ukraine’s war with Russia constitutes a direct threat to European security, opposing Ukraine’s EU membership and interpreting Ukraine’s demand to halt Russian energy imports as hostile toward Hungary. This stance was reinforced in diplomatic discussions between Orbán and Russian President Vladimir Putin. Ukraine’s refusal to permit Russian oil transit via the Friendship Pipeline further strained relations with Hungary, triggering economic and diplomatic consequences. While some, including Ukrainian officials and Estonian Foreign Minister Kaja Kallas, frame the conflict as Ukraine’s own war—not Europe’s—this perspective is overshadowed by the war’s profound impact on European politics, public opinion, and security doctrine, particularly in Germany and the Baltics. The (Russia, Ukraine) relation thus remains the most significant geopolitical fault line in contemporary Europe, encompassing military, economic, informational, and diplomatic dimensions.&lt;SEP&gt;Russian media suggest Russia could cut off oil and gas supplies to Ukraine if Hungary supports military aid, indicating energy as a strategic lever.&lt;SEP&gt;A peace agreement between Russia and Ukraine is considered impossible without Ukraine's consent, according to Robert Fico.&lt;SEP&gt;Russia is directing North Korean troops to Ukraine.&lt;SEP&gt;Russia is engaged in a war against Ukraine, to which North Korean soldiers were sent to participate.&lt;SEP&gt;Russia is waging an illegal aggressive war in Ukraine, which has resulted in the deaths of North Korean soldiers fighting alongside Russian forces.&lt;SEP&gt;Russia invaded Ukraine, which is the conflict that North Korea and Kim Jong Un are supporting.</data>
  <data key="d10">aggression,armed conflict,combat experience,conditionality,conflict,disinformation,economic pressure,electronic warfare,energy leverage,energy policy,energy sanctions,intelligence gathering,invasion,media manipulation,military aggression,military conflict,military deployment,operational experience,oppose,peace negotiation,pipeline transit,strategic threat,territorial ambition,troop transfer,war,weaken support</data>
