<edge source="Russia" target="Kremlin">
  <data key="d8">8.0</data>
  <data key="d9">The Kremlin is the central governing authority of Russia and the primary center of power representing Vladimir Putin and the Russian state. It directs Russia’s military and information strategies, including operations targeting the Baltic States, Hungary, and the European Union, and exercises centralized control over foreign influence efforts by reviewing and approving or rejecting proposals from agencies such as the SVR. The Kremlin has been critiqued for strategic overestimations of Russian military capabilities, particularly in the war with Ukraine, where it allegedly misjudged both its own forces and the resilience of Ukrainian and European defenses. According to analyses, including those by Razvedos, the Kremlin continues to underestimate European military preparedness, believing that its battlefield experience in Ukraine will enable it to defeat Western armies—despite acknowledged limitations in areas such as electronic warfare. Additionally, the Kremlin is implicitly aligned with Putin’s positions on critical national interests, including asset retention and pipeline transit, reinforcing its role as the supreme decision-making body for both domestic and foreign policy across military, intelligence, and geopolitical domains.</data>
  <data key="d10">alignment,authority,authority structure,command structure,decision-making,governing entity,institutional representation,leadership,military doctrine,strategic belief,strategic misjudgment</data>
  <data key="d11">chunk-fa2b47c359e22a6528975dcd5b3e91a6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7d8dc136c80cd91ef2cf9ad9756a4d52&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1a126839f1ff6597735159d84aa24a61&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b80d70d8670ebee7e64e3613a75c65de&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-02f8127f57647c6f52ac2f580f293f65&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8fa6adba441e776b293e92361b9880d1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-35ef5418fbb73e10428a076cc8117782</data>
