<edge source="Russia" target="Hungary">
  <data key="d8">28.0</data>
  <data key="d9">The relationship between Hungary and Russia is characterized by a deep, strategically coordinated political, economic, and intelligence alignment, primarily driven by Prime Minister Viktor Orbán’s government. Hungary has consistently resisted EU-wide efforts to reduce dependence on Russian energy, continuing to spend approximately €5 billion annually on Russian fossil fuels—a policy Orbán defends as vital to maintaining energy security and low fuel prices, in contrast to neighboring countries like Poland, Bulgaria, and Czechia. Hungary receives discounted Russian crude oil, a pricing scheme that benefits state-aligned entities rather than the general public, further entrenching economic ties.

Diplomatically, Hungary maintains close contact with Russia, including direct communication between Hungarian and Russian foreign ministers during EU meetings. Under Orbán, Hungary has avoided publicly blaming Russia for attacks such as the Mukachevo missile strike and the bombing of the Brody Pumping Station, signaling diplomatic restraint or alignment with Moscow. Hungary’s Foreign Minister, Siyarta, has acted in coordination with Russia to influence EU sanctions policy, reflecting a deliberate alignment with Russian interests. Russia views Hungary as a critical asset within the EU, investing heavily in sustaining Orbán’s political power through intelligence operations, media manipulation, and cyber espionage. Russian actors, including the SVR, have treated Hungary as an operational field akin to Cold War targets, deploying active measures to influence public opinion and electoral outcomes.

Russian interference has intensified since February, with operations previously directed at Moldova now redirected to Hungary using the same personnel and tools. Disinformation campaigns have falsely portrayed Hungary’s political opposition as Western puppets aiming to provoke nuclear war, aiming to sway voters in favor of Orbán’s Fidesz party. Allegations persist that Russian intelligence has infiltrated Orbán’s inner circle and influenced Hungarian media to promote pro-Moscow narratives, including false claims about Ukrainian individuals. There are also reports that Hungarian government and private aircraft have transported cash and valuables from Russia.

While Russian propagandists are invited to Hungary, public sentiment is not uniformly supportive—evidenced by crowds chanting “Russians, go home!”—highlighting domestic resistance to Moscow’s influence. European Union members fear Hungary may be leaking sensitive information to Russia and undermining EU unity. Critics, including Polish Foreign Minister Sikorski, have drawn parallels between Hungary’s posture and historical alignments with invading powers, notably referencing the Soviet Red Army’s 1956 invasion of Budapest. Overall, Hungary prioritizes energy autonomy and political sovereignty through alignment with Russia, while Russia leverages this partnership to fracture European cohesion and consolidate influence within the EU, with some observers alleging Hungary is subordinating its national interests to Vladimir Putin’s strategic agenda.&lt;SEP&gt;Hungary sources 90% of its oil and 95% of its gas from Russia, and Russia is constructing Hungary's atomic power station.&lt;SEP&gt;If Ukraine is defeated, Hungary could become a strategic Russian platform in the heart of Europe, enabling long-term threats to European security.&lt;SEP&gt;Russia exerts increasing influence over Hungary through political alignment and diplomatic ties, leading Hungary to depend on Russian support.&lt;SEP&gt;Russia engaged in coordinated diplomatic and strategic discussions with Hungarian officials, which were perceived as subservient and contributed to domestic backlash in Hungary.&lt;SEP&gt;Hungary is portrayed as pragmatically maintaining vital energy imports from Russia and expressing willingness to engage in dialogue with Russia.</data>
