<edge source="European Union" target="Hungary">
  <data key="d8">30.0</data>
  <data key="d9">The relationship between the European Union and Hungary is marked by profound institutional tension, strategic divergence, and serious security concerns, despite Hungary’s formal status as a member state. Under Prime Minister Viktor Orbán, Hungary has repeatedly obstructed key EU initiatives, particularly those related to sanctions against Russia and financial support for Ukraine. Hungary blocked the 20th package of EU sanctions, delayed the 18th, and demanded exemptions to continue purchasing Russian gas and oil, citing threats to its energy independence. It has also opposed the use of frozen Russian assets to fund Ukrainian reparations, condemned EU aid to Ukraine as wasteful, and advocated redirecting funds toward domestic priorities like healthcare and education. Notably, Hungary vetoed Ukraine’s EU membership application, arguing it would entangle the Union in the war.

Despite this obstructionism, Hungary has occasionally cooperated: it approved the €90 billion credit package for Ukraine at the December EU summit—a commitment EU Commission President Antonio Costa insists must be honored—and supported the EU’s fact-finding mission to Ukraine, even advocating for Hungarian representation in it. Hungary’s Foreign Minister, Siyarto (also referenced as Siyarta), has influenced EU negotiation frameworks by pushing for specific minority rights language in Ukraine’s accession talks, while simultaneously being accused of leveraging EU discussions to advance Russian interests, including lobbying to remove Russian individuals from sanctions lists without legal basis. These actions, along with confirmed cyber intrusions into Hungarian state networks and physical leaks at EU meetings, have led to Hungary’s exclusion from sensitive EU deliberations. Member states such as Germany, France, Poland, and the UK now form smaller, trusted groups (e.g., E3, E4, Weimar Triangle) to avoid sharing classified information with Hungary due to fears of espionage.

Hungary’s conduct has also triggered financial consequences: although entitled to €19 billion in EU funding, it lost €1 billion permanently due to failure to meet rule-of-law reform conditions. Additionally, Hungary has been accused of violating EU principles by seizing funds from another member state’s bank and endorsing hostage diplomacy. The EU granted Hungary a special exemption permitting below-market-rate imports of Russian oil—a privilege Orbán uses to justify his energy policy—yet Hungary’s overall trade with Russia has declined under sanctions, prompting Budapest to seek alternative economic partnerships.

Hungarian state media frequently frame EU actions as attempts to undermine Hungary’s economy, suppress its energy autonomy, and manipulate public information. Yet, approximately 80% of the Hungarian population continues to support EU membership, revealing a stark disconnect between government rhetoric and public sentiment. Hungary remains a member of the European Union, but its actions—combining selective cooperation, systemic obstruction, and credible security breaches—have fundamentally challenged the Union’s foundational values of rule of law, solidarity, and confidentiality.&lt;SEP&gt;Hungary remains a member of the European Union, but its actions under Viktor Orbán have paralyzed key EU initiatives, creating tension within the union.&lt;SEP&gt;Donald Trump Jr. contrasted Viktor Orbán’s stance with the broader European Union context, implying Orbán represents an independent alternative within Europe.&lt;SEP&gt;The European Union restricted Hungary’s access to intelligence, accused it of spying for Russia, and launched an investigation into espionage activities.&lt;SEP&gt;Hungary is depicted as promising to restore ties with the European Union while resisting its pressure, indicating underlying political tension.</data>
