<edge source="Ukraine" target="Hungary">
  <data key="d8">20.0</data>
  <data key="d9">The relationship between Hungary and Ukraine is marked by deepening geopolitical friction, strategic hostility, and mutual accusations, particularly under the leadership of Hungarian Prime Minister Viktor Orbán. Hungary frames Ukraine as a threat to its energy security, primarily due to Ukraine’s blockade of the Druzhba (Friendship) oil pipeline, which Hungary claims has severely disrupted its energy supply. In response, Hungary has suspended the transit of critical shipments to Ukraine until the pipeline is fully restored, while also seizing Ukrainian funds and threatening further similar actions. Hungary has adopted a resolution limiting financial support to Ukraine and opposes Ukraine’s accession to the European Union, viewing it as a potential erosion of its national veto power and sovereignty.

Hungarian state-controlled media consistently portrays Ukraine not as a victim of Russian aggression but as an ungrateful, corrupt, and ideological adversary, fostering domestic hostility. Ukrainian officials have condemned Hungary’s actions as violations of international norms and demanded official explanations, citing the detention of Ukrainian vehicles and financial seizures as evidence of coercive behavior. Ukraine perceives Hungary’s energy-related measures as deliberate attempts to destabilize its government and pressure Budapest into policy concessions.

Allegations extend beyond energy: Hungary is accused of seeking to provoke internal chaos in Ukraine to foster a more favorable political environment, while elements within Ukrainian special services are alleged to have attempted to influence Hungarian elections. Despite these tensions, a limited commercial trade route historically existed between Tiszókecske in Hungary and Ukraine, facilitating weekly shipments of alcohol and beverages through the business of László Kócs. These conflicting dynamics—ranging from high-stakes geopolitical obstruction to minor commercial exchanges—reflect a relationship defined by strategic rivalry, mutual distrust, and asymmetrical leverage, with energy dependency serving as the central axis of conflict.&lt;SEP&gt;Hungary seized €35 million, $40 million, and 9 kg of gold from Oschadbank, holding the assets as leverage to force Ukraine to repair the Druzhba pipeline.&lt;SEP&gt;Hungary was the target and origin of disinformation portraying Ukraine as corrupt and hostile, including fabricated stories about gold shipments and dead Hungarian soldiers.&lt;SEP&gt;Hungary’s relations with Ukraine have deteriorated due to its alignment with Russia and opposition to Ukrainian interests.&lt;SEP&gt;Hungarian state media falsely accused Ukraine of planning violent unrest and using snipers and drone operators to provoke chaos after the elections.&lt;SEP&gt;Mátyás, the future prime minister of Hungary, asserted that Ukraine cannot be forced to surrender its territory when negotiating peace, affirming Ukraine's sovereign right to determine its own conditions.</data>
  <data key="d10">blockade,condition,conflict,create chaos,demand for explanation,destabilize,deteriorate relations,diplomatic confirmation,diplomatic leverage,diplomatic protest,diplomatic tension,disinformation,economic impact,economic pressure,election interference,energy dispute,energy disruption,external interference,false accusation,false conflict,financial restriction,financial retaliation,financial seizure,geopolitical strategy,hostage diplomacy,hostility,ideological opposition,lack of support,peace terms,policy opposition,political conflict,political opposition,shipment,sovereignty,strategic conflict,suspension,territorial integrity,trade route,transit</data>
