<edge source="Ukraine" target="Viktor Orbán">
  <data key="d8">9.0</data>
  <data key="d9">The relationship between Ukraine and Viktor Orbán is characterized by deep hostility and strategic confrontation. Viktor Orbán, Prime Minister of Hungary, has explicitly labeled Ukraine an enemy of Hungary, citing Ukraine’s pressure on the European Union to halt purchases of Russian energy as a primary grievance. He has repeatedly blocked €90 billion in EU financial assistance to Ukraine, asserting that such aid will not proceed until Ukraine restores Russian oil transit through the Druzhba pipeline—a move he frames as essential for Hungarian and Slovak energy security. Orbán accuses Ukraine of enforcing a harmful oil pipeline blockade and engaging in blackmail against Hungary and Slovakia, portraying these actions as deliberate economic aggression.

Orbán has also leveraged the war in Ukraine as a central theme in his domestic political campaigns, using it to justify crackdowns on dissent and stoke public fear. He has claimed, without public evidence, that Ukraine plans physical attacks on his family, a narrative he employs to rally support for authoritarian measures and frame foreign interference as an existential threat. These assertions have been widely criticized as baseless and politically motivated. Furthermore, Orbán’s obstruction of EU financial and political support for Ukraine is seen as a significant undermining of international solidarity, with analysts noting that his blockade is expected to persist even if he is not re-elected.

Critics allege that Orbán’s regime uses the Ukraine conflict as a distraction from domestic corruption, contrasting his approach with that of his predecessor János Mádiár, who avoided politicizing Ukraine to focus on financial crimes within Hungary. Overall, Orbán’s stance toward Ukraine is marked by geopolitical defiance, populist rhetoric, and a deliberate erosion of EU cohesion on Ukraine policy.&lt;SEP&gt;Viktor Orbán opposed Ukraine’s interests by blocking EU aid and sanctions against Russia, and by facilitating Russian geopolitical influence.</data>
  <data key="d10">aid denial,blackmail,blockade,condition,criticism,enmity,funding blockade,hostility,obstruction,opposition,political framing,political strategy,political_distraction,security narrative,war rhetoric</data>
