<edge source="Ukraine" target="Orbán">
  <data key="d8">8.0</data>
  <data key="d9">Orbán, the Prime Minister of Hungary, has pursued a confrontational stance toward Ukraine, leveraging energy policy and domestic political rhetoric to advance his strategic and electoral objectives. He blocked €90 billion in EU funding allocated to Ukraine and halted diesel fuel supplies, citing Ukraine’s refusal to restore the Druzhba (Friendship) Pipeline, which he claims has been damaged due to Ukrainian actions. Orbán has repeatedly framed Ukraine as a threat to Hungary’s energy security, blaming Kyiv for pipeline disruptions and portraying the situation as blackmail or intimidation directed at Hungarian leadership. His election campaign featured anti-Ukrainian propaganda, including baseless accusations that political opponents were spending money on Ukrainian gold bars, while he accused domestic crowds of promoting Ukrainian interests and seeking a pro-Ukrainian government. Orbán sought to force Ukraine into concessions over the Druzhba Pipeline ahead of Hungary’s April 12 elections, aiming to secure a political victory by portraying himself as a defender of national sovereignty. Notably, he previously characterized Ukraine as not an independent country but later clarified that Ukraine would not be treated as a puppet state, suggesting a tactical shift or attempt to recalibrate his public position. Despite Orbán’s assertions of Ukrainian weakness, Ukraine’s financial resilience has undermined his narrative, potentially turning his political strategy into a liability and reinforcing Ukraine’s strategic advantage in the broader geopolitical contest.</data>
