<edge source="Hungary" target="Orbán">
  <data key="d8">17.0</data>
  <data key="d9">Viktor Orbán is the Prime Minister of Hungary and the central political figure leading the ruling party, whose policies and control over media have profoundly shaped national discourse, particularly regarding sovereignty, the Russia-Ukraine war, and political opposition. Orbán has governed Hungary for 16 years, during which approximately 80% of the country’s news media became government-aligned, consolidating his influence over public perception. He champions a platform of national sovereignty, encapsulated in the slogan “For a Sovereign Hungary,” and consistently opposes external interference, framing EU and Ukrainian demands as threats to Hungarian interests. Orbán has publicly rejected calls to redirect Hungarian funds to Ukraine, claiming such efforts serve foreign agendas rather than domestic needs, and has positioned Hungary as maintaining an independent, moderate stance on the war—though critics argue this stance aligns with Russian interests, particularly through continued economic ties to Russian oil. His administration has been accused of enriching himself and allies via corrupt patronage networks, resisting anti-corruption reforms, and triggering the freezing of EU funds. Orbán’s electoral practices have drawn scrutiny, with investigations highlighting systemic manipulation, while his anti-Ukrainian and anti-EU rhetoric has dominated campaign messaging. Despite his long-standing dominance, public dissent has grown: tens of thousands have protested for regime change, and at one rally, attendees openly insulted him and demanded his departure, signaling a significant erosion of prior support. Orbán’s leadership is thus characterized by a dual narrative: one of sovereign self-determination endorsed by his base, and another of authoritarian consolidation and corruption condemned by domestic opposition and international observers.&lt;SEP&gt;Orbán is the incumbent Prime Minister of Hungary leading the government during a critical election period marked by internal and external political pressures.</data>
  <data key="d10">corruption,election campaign,election_campaigning,governance,government,influence,leadership,media control,national representation,national sovereignty,policy representation,political gathering,political leadership,political rhetoric,political slogan,political stance,political support,political_activity,power consolidation,rally,regime,representation</data>
  <data key="d11">chunk-cf472d3981c26e07231b309328f0597b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c1d344e42d77e1e71d20f49e3f03482d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d6a8f4f06a47d67e1f0a25d123d913f2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d51a096074bc48afe9e2e842bcfbc382&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-26fcbf6510a404d136a66a46e0584357&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b27aeca6858b7e54f862c47192fbcea2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ec12d27878bbf1f79c741b043b995fd5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4bd0a283b39238236a064e8afb069c87&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e4089c9c991c6402b317d88ca6848ab9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ce845ea082895ffef253ac499ba46794&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b6bcd039eb9ab628a1ffb566a855dd2b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1704b3bc09f596547c35a95941e29e5f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-765485889ec9c96686562866ad272ef6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0c1646bf239b09baeadccfb2da8543a8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-31e87cfbc838591dc342c244d9dff43a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-81e671facba3c370c9128965308146dd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e1c1527de328b9a19ce7197568a1196b</data>
